# Image Processing - microbe CV



When using computer vision to analyse and work with microscopy captures, it helps to be able to make out cell boundaries. This can be done with thresholding, which can be done in several ways. 

I found both[ skimage](https://scikit-image.org/docs/stable/api/skimage.html) and [mahotas](http://mahotas.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) to be useful for these tasks. 

I will begin with skimage. Skimage can be used for a variety of CV tasks. Many microscopy captures are done with Nikon equipment, which outputs nd2 files. Skimage has modules that help handle these file types. 

To work with nd2 files, import the module

```text
from scipy import ndimage as nd
```

Images will need to be brought in and assigned to local variables in the notebook. Then thresholding can be applied to the nd2 capture.

Sobel thresholds are often used for edge detection

{% hint style="info" %}
 The **Sobel operator**, sometimes called the **Sobel–Feldman operator** or **Sobel filter**, is used in [image processing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_processing) and [computer vision](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_vision), particularly within [edge detection](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_detection) algorithms where it creates an image emphasising edges.  The Sobel–Feldman operator is based on convolving the image with a small, separable, and integer-valued filter in the horizontal and vertical directions and is therefore relatively inexpensive in terms of computations. 

source: [Sobel operator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sobel_operator)
{% endhint %}

Skimage offers a few methods for sobel thresholding:

```text
zx = ndimage.sobel(mb_img, axis = 0, mode = 'constant')  
zy = ndimage.sobel(mb_img, axis = 1, mode = 'constant')  
sobl = np.hypot(zx, zy)  
plt.imshow(sobl)  
plt.show()
```

![](data:image/png;base64,)

```text
zx = ndimage.sobel(mb_img, axis = 0, mode = 'reflect')  
zy = ndimage.sobel(mb_img, axis = 1, mode = 'reflect')  
sobl = np.hypot(zx, zy)  
plt.imshow(sobl)  
plt.show()
```

![](data:image/png;base64,)

```text
from skimage import data, io, filters
edges = filters.sobel(mb_img)
io.imshow(edges)
io.show()
```
